<subSubSection id="C31EEBFFBB38C85F7DFDFC9E2A91C863" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB38C85F7DFDFC9E2A89CB5A" blockId="21.[140,1108,588,1672]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7DFDFC9E2A4ACDFD" bold="true" box="[185,312,870,896]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7DFDFC9E2A41CDFD" box="[185,307,870,896]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7C05FC9F2973CDFC" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[321,513,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifascia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7C05FC9F2973CDFC" box="[321,513,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">Hypotrix trifascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is smaller than 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7FF8FC9F2848CDFC" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[700,826,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7FF8FC9F29A0CDFD" box="[700,722,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7FA7FC9F2848CDFC" box="[739,826,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in size (forewing length 
<quantity id="4CFC1591BB38C85F7DC8FC722A7CCDD9" box="[140,270,906,932]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" unit="mm" value="12.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="11.0">11–14 mm</quantity>
). It is variable in forewing ground color, varying from pale yellowish buff to dark reddish orange. As the name implies, the two transverse lines and the subterminal line are prominently marked by light and dark lines and are relatively straight and at least partially parallel, creating its distinctive “three-fascia” appearance. The hindwing is translucent white with a slight pinkish blush. The 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7F98FBEF2807CA4C" box="[732,885,1047,1073]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">male genitalia</emphasis>
are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7DEFFBC32A55CA29" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[171,295,1082,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7DEFFBC32BB3CA29" box="[171,193,1083,1108]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7D94FBC22A55CA29" box="[208,295,1082,1108]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7CC0FBC32972CA29" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[388,512,1082,1108]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifascia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7CC0FBC32AE8CA29" box="[388,410,1083,1108]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7CEEFBC22972CA29" box="[426,512,1082,1108]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">trifascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the dorsal process of the sacculus is pointed and the saccular flap is less extensive. Th e uncus is unique in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7FA8FBA6281ACA0A" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[748,872,1117,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifascia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7FA8FBA62870CA0A" box="[748,770,1118,1143]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7E56FBA5281ACA0A" box="[786,872,1117,1143]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">trifascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; it is broad mesially, narrows subapically, and broad and truncated at apex. The vesica is about 2 × as long as the aedeagus, gently coiled, with two basal and one subbasal cornuti. The 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F794AFB5B2B98CA9C" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">female genitalia</emphasis>
are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7CB7FB3F2902CA9C" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[499,624,1223,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7CB7FB3F297BCA9D" box="[499,521,1223,1248]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7F5DFB3F2902CA9C" box="[537,624,1223,1249]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7F82FB3F2830CA9C" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[710,834,1223,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifascia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7F82FB3F29AECA9D" box="[710,732,1223,1248]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7FA8FB3F2830CA9C" box="[748,834,1223,1249]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">trifascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the ductus bursae has a posterior bulge to the left and right and a mesial bulge to the right, and the appendix bursae is short with a single coil.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB38C85F7DFDFAC92A91C863" blockId="21.[140,1108,588,1672]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7DFDFAC92A04CB37" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[185,374,1328,1354]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifascia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7DFDFAC92A04CB37" box="[185,374,1328,1354]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">Hypotrix trifascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7F12FAC9280ACB37" authority="(Schaus, 1894)" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Schaus" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[598,888,1328,1355]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Chloridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vigasia" status="comb. n.">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7F12FAC9291ECB37" box="[598,620,1329,1354]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7F3FFAC929B7CB37" box="[635,709,1329,1354]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">vigasia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF95C585BB38C85F7F97FAC8281CCB37" author="Schaus W" box="[723,878,1328,1354]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" pagination="223 - 244" refId="ref14078" refString="Schaus W (1894) New species of Noctuidae from tropical America. Transactions of the American Entomological Society 21: 223 - 244." type="journal article" year="1894">Schaus, 1894</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A243D91DBB38C85F7EC7FAC82898CB36" box="[899,1002,1328,1355]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7EC7FAC828B4CB37" bold="true" box="[899,966,1328,1354]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">comb</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7E97FAC82891CB37" bold="true" box="[979,995,1328,1354]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">n</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
from the State of 
<collectingRegion id="49C07696BB38C85F7DA1FAAC2A35CB13" box="[229,327,1364,1390]" country="Mexico" name="Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">Veracruz</collectingRegion>
in southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="F313F8E4BB38C85F7CBAFAAB2927CB10" box="[510,597,1363,1389]" name="Mexico" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, but the forewing of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7E78FAAC28DBCB10" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Schaus" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[828,937,1364,1390]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Chloridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vigasia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7E78FAAC2820CB10" box="[828,850,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7E1BFAAC28DBCB10" box="[863,937,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">vigasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is buffy-brown with the maculation muted, and the subterminal line is not as straight as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7E97FA8F2F3ECBEC" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[979,1100,1399,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifascia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7E97FA8F289BCBED" box="[979,1001,1399,1424]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7EB2FA8F2F3ECBEC" box="[1014,1100,1399,1425]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">trifascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF95C585BB38C85F7DC8FA622A52CBC9" author="Poole RW" box="[140,288,1434,1460]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" refId="ref14046" refString="Poole RW (1989) Lepidopterorum Catalogus (New Series). Fascicle 118 Noctuidae. E. J. Brill, New York, 3 pts., 1314 pp." type="book" year="1989">Poole (1989)</bibRefCitation>
lists 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7C19FA632ABFCBC9" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Schaus" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[349,461,1434,1460]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Chloridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vigasia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7C19FA632A01CBC9" box="[349,371,1435,1460]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7CC7FA632ABFCBC9" box="[387,461,1435,1460]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">vigasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7FDCFA622880CBC9" authority="Blasquez, 1870" authorityName="Blasquez" authorityYear="1870" box="[664,1010,1434,1460]" class="Insecta" family="Bombycidae" genus="Bombyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agavis">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7FDCFA622848CBC9" box="[664,826,1434,1460]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">Bombyx agavis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF95C585BB38C85F7E07FA622880CBC9" author="Blasquez I" box="[835,1010,1434,1460]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" pagination="282 - 290" refId="ref13582" refString="Blasquez I (1870) Fauna indigena. Insectos del Maguey. Naturaleza 1: 282 - 290." type="journal article" year="1870">Blasquez, 1870</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but the location of the 
<typeStatus id="54BF06D6BB38C85F7C73FA462A03CBA5" box="[311,369,1470,1496]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">types</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB38C85F7CD1FA452947CBAA" authorityName="Blasquez" authorityYear="1870" box="[405,565,1469,1495]" class="Insecta" family="Bombycidae" genus="Bombyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agavis">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB38C85F7CD1FA452947CBAA" box="[405,565,1469,1495]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">Bombyx agavis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, if any exist, is unknown and the original paintings (
<bibRefCitation id="EF95C585BB38C85F7D8DFA182A08CB87" author="Blasquez I" box="[201,378,1504,1530]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" pagination="282 - 290" refId="ref13582" refString="Blasquez I (1870) Fauna indigena. Insectos del Maguey. Naturaleza 1: 282 - 290." type="journal article" year="1870">Blasquez, 1870</bibRefCitation>
, Figs 6, 9) are not identifiable as a noctuid and may be a cossid (Martin Honey, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31EEBFFBB38C85C7DFDF9DE2B84CAFE" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="247" pageId="21" pageNumber="246" type="distribution">
